<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>7</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<HR style="margin-bottom:9.6px; padding-top:9.6px" noshade size=1.333>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=center><B>ENDURANCE 
EXPLORATION GROUP, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL 
STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>JUNE 30, 2016</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>(Unaudited)</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>NOTE A - SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING 
POLICIES</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>A summary of the significant accounting 
policies applied in the preparation of the accompanying consolidated financial 
statements follows.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Description of Business</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Endurance Exploration Group, Inc. (formerly 
Tecton Corporation) (the &#147;Company&#148;) was incorporated under the laws of
the State of Nevada on January 19, 2006, as a wholly-owned subsidiary of Hemis 
Corporation. &nbsp;On December 1, 2006 Hemis declared a dividend of Tecton 
shares to all shareholders as of that date and concurrently cancelled its share 
ownership in the Company. &nbsp;The effect of this dividend declaration and 
share cancellation was that Tecton was spun off as an independent company. 
&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On November 8, 2013, the Board of Directors 
approved a change of the Company&#146;s fiscal year from January 31, to December
31. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On December 31, 2013, the Company acquired 
100% of the membership interests of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC 
(&#147;Endurance LLC&#148;), a Florida limited liability company, in exchange 
for 20,550,539 shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock being issued to the 
former members. Endurance LLC is now a wholly owned subsidiary with its 
operations being the Company&#146;s primary focus. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><U>Endurance Exploration Group LLC</U> 
&#150; is engaged in the archaeologically sensitive exploration and recovery of 
deep-ocean shipwrecks throughout the world. We intend to recover bullion 
precious metals, numismatic-grade coinage, high-value non-ferrous metals and
other valuable cargos from both historic and modern shipwrecks.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On January 2, 2014, the Company changed its 
name to Endurance Exploration Group, Inc.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our corporate headquarters are located in 
Clearwater, Florida.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Principles of consolidation and basis of 
presentation</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>These consolidated financial statements 
include the assets and liabilities of the Endurance Exploration Group, Inc. 
(formerly Tecton Corporation) and its subsidiaries as of June 30, 2016. 
&nbsp;The acquisition of the membership interests of Endurance LLC and its 
wholly owned Panamanian subsidiary formed to hold the registry of a research 
vessel occurred as of the close of its business on December 31, 2013.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The unaudited interim consolidated financial
statements have been prepared pursuant to the rules and regulations of the U.S. 
Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;). &nbsp;Certain 
information and footnote disclosures normally included in annual financial 
statements prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted 
in the United States have been condensed or omitted pursuant to such SEC rules 
and regulations, although the Company believes that the disclosures made are 
adequate to make the information not misleading. It is suggested that these 
consolidated financial statements be read in conjunction with the consolidated 
financial statements and the notes thereto, included in the Company&#146;s 
latest Annual Report on Form 10-K.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In the opinion of management, all 
adjustments consisting of normal recurring adjustments necessary for a fair 
statement of the financial position at June 30, 2016 and the results of 
operations for the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 and cash 
flows for the six months ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 have been made. &nbsp;All 
material intercompany transactions have been eliminated.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>8</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<HR style="margin-bottom:9.6px; padding-top:9.6px" noshade size=1.333>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Use of Estimates</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The preparation of financial statements in 
conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles requires 
management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of
assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at 
the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and 
expenses during the reporting period. Actual results could differ from those 
estimates.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Subsequent Events</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company has evaluated subsequent events 
through the filing of this Form 10-Q, to assess the need for potential 
recognition or disclosure in this report. Based upon this evaluation, management
determined that all subsequent events that require recognition in the financial 
statements have been included.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Cash and Cash Equivalents</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>For purposes of the Statements of Cash
Flows, the Company considers all highly liquid debt instruments purchased with a
maturity date of three months or less to be cash equivalents. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Offering Costs</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>As of June 30, 2016, the Company has 
incurred $30,875 of deferred offering costs associated with the planned sale of 
securities. &nbsp;This amount is included on the balance sheet in prepaid 
expenses and deferred costs. &nbsp;These costs will be netted against proceeds 
upon completion of the offering, or they will be expensed if the offering is 
unsuccessful. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Fixed Assets</U><B> </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Fixed assets are stated at historical cost. 
Depreciation is provided using the straight-line method at rates based on the 
assets&#146; estimated useful lives which are normally between three and ten 
years. &nbsp;When retired or otherwise disposed, the related carrying value and 
accumulated depreciation are removed from the respective accounts and the net 
difference less any amount realized from disposition, is reflected in earnings. 
Leasehold improvements are amortized over their estimated useful lives or lease 
term, if shorter. Equipment and major overhaul items (such as engines or 
generators) that enhance or extend the useful life of vessel related assets 
qualify to be capitalized and depreciated over the useful life or remaining life
of that asset, whichever is shorter. Certain major repair items required by 
industry standards to ensure a vessel&#146;s seaworthiness also qualify to be 
capitalized and depreciated over the period of time until the next scheduled 
planned major maintenance for that item. All other repairs and maintenance are 
accounted for under the direct-expensing method and are expensed when incurred. 
</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Impairment of Long-Lived Assets</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company reviews long-lived assets for 
impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the 
carrying amount of such assets may not be recoverable. &nbsp;Fair value is 
determined based on discounted cash flows or appraised values, depending on the 
nature of the assets. As of June 30, 2016 and 2015, there were no impairment 
losses recognized for long-lived assets.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Income Taxes</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">The 
Company uses the liability method to record income tax activity. Deferred taxes 
are determined based upon the estimated future tax effects of differences 
between the financial reporting and tax reporting bases of assets and 
liabilities given the provisions of currently enacted tax laws.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The accounting for uncertainty in income 
taxes recognized in an enterprise&#146;s financial statements uses the threshold
of more-likely-than-not to be sustained upon examination for inclusion or 
exclusion. Measurement of the tax uncertainty occurs if the recognition 
threshold has been met. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>9</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<HR style="margin-bottom:9.6px; padding-top:9.6px" noshade size=1.333>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><U>Net Earnings (Losses) Per Common Share</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company computes earnings (loss) per 
share by dividing net earnings (loss) by the weighted average number of shares
of common stock and dilutive common stock equivalents outstanding during the 
year. Dilutive common stock equivalents may&nbsp;consist of shares issuable upon
conversion of convertible preferred shares and the exercise of the Company's 
stock options (calculated using the treasury stock method). &nbsp;As of June 30,
2016, there were 5,574,000 common stock equivalents that were anti-dilutive and 
were not included in the calculation. Common stock issuable is considered 
outstanding as of the original approval date for purposes of earnings per share 
computations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<A NAME="page_39"></A><P style="margin:0px"><U>Fair Value of Financial 
Instruments</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The fair value of financial instruments, 
which include cash, loans receivable, accounts payable and accrued expenses and 
advances from related parties were estimated to approximate their carrying 
values due to the immediate or short-term maturity of these financial 
instruments. Management is of the opinion that the Company is not exposed to 
significant interest, currency or credit risks arising from financial 
instruments.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><U>Comprehensive 
Income</U></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">The 
Company records comprehensive income as the change in equity of a business 
during a period from transactions and other events and circumstances from non-
owner sources. It includes all changes in equity during a period except those 
resulting from investments by owners and distributions to owners. Other 
comprehensive income (loss) includes foreign currency translation adjustments 
and unrealized gains and losses on available-for-sale securities. As of June 30,
2016 the Company had no items that represent comprehensive loss and, therefore, 
has not included a schedule of comprehensive loss in the financial 
statements.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><U>Stock Based 
Compensation</U></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Stock
based compensation costs are measured at fair value on date of grant and 
recognition of compensation over the service period for awards expected to vest.
The Company determines the fair value of awards using the Black-Scholes 
valuation model. </FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<A NAME="page_40"></A><P style="margin:0px"><U>New Accounting 
Pronouncements</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company reviews new accounting standards
as issued. No new standards had any material effect on these financial 
statements. The accounting pronouncements issued subsequent to the date of these
financial statements that were considered significant by management were 
evaluated for the potential effect on these consolidated financial statements. 
Management does not believe any of the subsequent pronouncements will have a 
material effect on these consolidated financial statements as presented and does
not anticipate the need for any future restatement of these consolidated 
financial statements because of the retro-active application of any accounting 
pronouncements issued subsequent to June 30, 2016 through the date these 
financial statements were issued.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>NOTE B &#150; GOING CONCERN MATTERS</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The accompanying financial statements have 
been prepared on a going concern basis, which contemplates the realization of 
assets and the satisfaction of liabilities in the normal course of business. As 
shown in the accompanying financial statements for the period January 19, 2006
(date of inception) to June 30, 2016, the Company incurred losses of $6,745,493.
The Company has minimal liquid assets. These factors, among others, indicate 
that the Company will be unable to continue as a going concern for a reasonable 
period of time.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company's existence is dependent upon 
management's ability to develop profitable operations and resolve its liquidity 
problems. The accompanying financial statements do not include any adjustments 
that might result should the Company be unable to continue as a going 
concern.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>NOTE C &#150; ACQUISITION OF ENDURANCE EXPLORATION 
GROUP LLC MEMBERSHIP INTERESTS</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">On December 31, 2013, the Company acquired 100% of the 
membership interests of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC, a Florida limited 
liability company (&#147;Endurance LLC&#148;) by issuing 20,550,539 shares of 
its common stock.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>10</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<HR style="margin-bottom:9.6px; padding-top:9.6px" noshade size=1.333>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The majority shareholders of the Company 
also held a majority interest in Endurance LLC, and maintained controlling 
interests in both entities both before and after the transaction. 
&nbsp;Accordingly, the acquisition has been accounted for as a corporate 
reorganization because of the common control. &nbsp;The book value of Endurance 
LLC at the time of the acquisition was as follows:</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<TR><TD style="margin-top:0px; padding-left:9.6px; padding-top:0px; padding-

width=92.467 colspan=2><P style="margin:0px">Cash</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<A NAME="page_41"></A><P style="margin:0px"><B>NOTE D &#150; PREPAID EXPENSES 
AND DEFERRED COSTS</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On May 15, 2015, the Company entered into an
agreement with Eclipse Group, Inc. to provide services, equipment and/or 
personnel in support of anticipated Endurance salvage projects, to inspect and 
recover one or more shipwreck cargoes located by Endurance. &nbsp;The Company 
issued 2,000,000 common shares at $.25 per share with a value of $500,000.
&nbsp;These shares represent a prepayment for Eclipse services pursuant to a 
schedule of agreed upon costs and rates. &nbsp;Eclipse will invoice the Company 
on a monthly basis as services are rendered. &nbsp;During the year ended 
December 31, 2015, Eclipse rendered $150,000 of the services outlined in this 
agreement. &nbsp;As of June 30, 2016, the Company has not received any 
additional invoices for services outlined in this agreement, and consequently 
the remaining balance of $350,000 is included in prepaid expenses along with 
$30,875 of deferred issuance costs for a total of $380,875 at June 30, 2016.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">On 
December 31, 2013, the Company completed the purchase of 100% of the membership 
interests of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC (&#147;Endurance LLC&#148;), from 
its members, Micah Eldred and Carl Dilley, in exchange for 20,550,539 shares of 
the Company&#146;s common stock, valued at $0.0186 per share, based upon the net
book value of the assets of Endurance LLC, $381,173 as of December 31, 
2013.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">On 
December 31, 2013, as a consequence of acquiring the membership interests of 
Endurance LLC, the Company assumed a liability of Endurance LLC to Micah Eldred 
under a demand promissory note, dated June 19, 2012, in the original principal 
amount of $60,000, bearing interest at 5%. &nbsp;The note has no stipulated 
maturity date, and the balance due under the note at June 30, 2016, including 
accrued interest, was $72,909.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">The 
Company has entered into a contract with Island Capital Management, LLC, which 
is related through common shareholders, to serve as its transfer agent. &nbsp;It
did not charge the Company for its services during the three and six months 
ended June 30, 2016 or 2015, as management has deemed it to be 
immaterial.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">The 
Company has entered into a contract with Proxy &amp; Printing, LLC, which is 
related through common shareholders, to provide the Company with printing and 
other services relating to its filings with the SEC. &nbsp;It did not charge the
Company for its services during the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 or 
2015, as management has deemed it to be immaterial.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">On 
June 23, 2014, the Company entered into a contract with Eclipse Group Inc. 
(&#147;Eclipse&#148;) for Eclipse to provide personnel and services to the 
Company in connection with the operation and monitoring of a remotely operated 
vehicle (&#147;ROV&#148;) in connection with our investigation of a suspected 
shipwreck located off the coast of New England. Steven Saint Amour, who serves 
as a member of the Company&#146;s Board of Directors, and Joan Saint Amour are 
the principal shareholders and officers of Eclipse. &nbsp;The contract provides 
that Eclipse will provide 2 people, including Mr. Saint Amour, for approximately
four 12-hour days to operate and monitor the ROV, which will be provided by the 
Company. &nbsp;The Company will issue 100,000 shares of common stock to Mr. 
Saint Amour, with an agreed value of $25,000, under the contract, and reimburse 
Eclipse in cash for its cost for the second ROV technician. &nbsp;The Company 
will also pay Eclipse in cash its cost plus 15% for all third party costs 
incurred by Eclipse, and provide Mr. Saint Amour and the second technician with 
food and lodging during the assignment.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On September 3, 2014, the Company entered 
into a contract with Overseas Marine Vessel Corp, LLC (&#147;OMVC&#148;) 
pursuant to which it will provide the Marine Vessel Manisee in support of an 
estimated 10-day mission to investigate, identify and recovery artifacts from 
one or more shipwrecks located in our search area off the coast of New England. 
&nbsp;We will reimburse OMVC in cash for all its out-of-pocket expenses only, 
including but not limited to, mooring, food, fuel, lube, satellite 
communications and crew costs. &nbsp;Toni Eldred, the spouse of Micah Eldred, is
a fifty percent owner of OMVC, and Micah Eldred is the co-manager of OMVC. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered 
into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC 
(&#147;Endeavour&#148;) relating to the conversion of indebtedness to Endeavour 
in the amount of $85,000. This amount represents the related party debt payable 
to Endeavour as of that date. &nbsp;The terms of the agreement allowed for 
Endeavour to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 per share.
&nbsp;Endeavour converted all of such debt into shares, as a result of which we 
issued 340,000 shares to Endeavour. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>12</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<HR style="margin-bottom:9.6px; padding-top:9.6px" noshade size=1.333>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered 
into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Micah Eldred relating to the conversion of
indebtedness to Micah Eldred in the amount of $143,333. This amount represents 
the related party debt payable to Micah Eldred as of that date. &nbsp;The terms 
of the agreement allowed for Micah Eldred to convert this debt into common stock
at $0.25 per share. &nbsp;Micah Eldred converted all of such debt into shares, 
as a result of which we issued 573,333 shares to Micah Eldred. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered 
into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Carl &amp; Heather Dilley relating to the 
conversion of indebtedness to Carl &amp; Heather Dilley in the amount of $45,867
and $25,800 respectively. This amount represents the related party debt payable 
to Carl &amp; Heather Dilley as of that date. &nbsp;The terms of the agreement 
allowed for Carl &amp; Heather Dilley to convert this debt into common stock at 
$0.25 per share. &nbsp;Carl &amp; Heather Dilley converted all of such debt into
shares, as a result of which we issued 183,467 and 103,200 shares to Carl &amp; 
Heather Dilley respectively.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During the six months ended June 30, 2016, 
Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC made net advances to the Company in the 
aggregate amount of $140,000, in order to provide the Company with funds to 
carry on its operations. &nbsp;These advances do not bear interest, are 
unsecured and have no specific terms of repayment. &nbsp;As of June 30, 2016, 
the aggregate amount of such advances outstanding was $235,500. Interest has not
been imputed on this balance as management has deemed it to be immaterial.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<A NAME="page_42"></A><P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT 
style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>NOTE G &#150; PREFERRED AND COMMON STOCK 
TRANSACTIONS AND REVERSE SPLIT</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered 
into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC 
(&#147;Endeavour&#148;) relating to the conversion of indebtedness to Endeavour 
in the amount of $85,000. This amount represents the related party debt payable 
to Endeavour as of that date. &nbsp;The terms of the agreement allowed for 
Endeavour to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 per share. 
&nbsp;Endeavour converted all of such debt into shares, as a result of which we 
issued 340,000 shares to Endeavour. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered 
into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Micah Eldred relating to the conversion of
indebtedness to Micah Eldred in the amount of $143,333. This amount represents 
the related party debt payable to Micah Eldred as of that date. &nbsp;The terms 
of the agreement allowed for Micah Eldred to convert this debt into common stock
at $0.25 per share. &nbsp;Micah Eldred converted all of such debt into shares, 
as a result of which we issued 573,333 shares to Micah Eldred. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">On 
February 12, 2015, the Company entered into a Debt Conversion Agreement with 
Carl &amp; Heather Dilley relating to the conversion of indebtedness to Carl 
&amp; Heather Dilley in the amount of $45,867 and $25,800 respectively. This 
amount represents the related party debt payable to Carl &amp; Heather Dilley as
of that date. &nbsp;The terms of the agreement allowed for Carl &amp; Heather 
Dilley to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 per share. &nbsp;Carl 
&amp; Heather Dilley converted all of such debt into shares, as a result of
which we issued 183,467 and 103,200 shares to Carl &amp; Heather Dilley 
respectively.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During April 2015, the Company issued 
600,000 common shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in 
fulfillment of stock subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During May 2015, the Company issued 200,000 
common shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in fulfillment of 
stock subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On May 15, 2015, the Company issued 
2,000,000 common shares to Eclipse Group, Inc. at $.25 per share as prepayment 
for certain salvage services pursuant to an agreement entered into on the same 
date. &nbsp;Steven Saint Amour, who serves as a member of our Board of 
Directors, and Joan Saint Amour are the principal shareholders and officers of 
Eclipse.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">On June 29, 2015, the Company issued 8,184 common shares 
at $.25 per share for services.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During July 2015, the Company issued 200,000
common shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in fulfillment of 
stock subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During August 2015, the Company issued 
1,670,000 common shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in 
fulfillment of stock subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During September 2015, the Company issued 
200,000 common shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in 
fulfillment of stock subscriptions received.</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><B>NOTE H &#150; WARRANTS AND OPTIONS</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">As of June 30, 2016, the Company had outstanding non-
qualified options to purchase 5,574,000 shares of our common stock at any time 
prior to their expiration dates, with an exercise price of $0.25 per share.</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px"><B>NOTE I &#150; INCOME 
TAXES</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>There is no current or deferred income tax 
expense or benefit allocated to continuing operations for the period ended June 
30, 2016 and 2015. The Company has not recognized an income tax benefit for its 
operating losses generated through June 30, 2016 based on uncertainties 
concerning the Company&#146;s ability to generate taxable income in future 
periods.&nbsp;&nbsp;The tax benefit is offset by a valuation allowance 
established against deferred tax assets arising from operating losses and other 
temporary differences, the realization of which could not be considered more 
likely than not.&nbsp;&nbsp;In future periods, tax benefits and related deferred
tax assets will be recognized when management considers realization of such 
amounts to be more likely than not.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>For income tax purposes the Company has 
available a net operating loss carry-forward of approximately $6,745,000 from 
inception to June 30, 2016, which will expire, unless used to offset future
federal taxable income beginning in 2024. &nbsp;The tax years ending December 
31, 2013 through December 31, 2014 are open for inspection by both Federal and 
State Agencies.</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Plan of Operation</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Side-scan sonar survey operations on Project
<I>Connaught</I> began in July of 2013. Over the course of this initial survey,
approximately 700 square miles were digitally mapped. This sonar imagery was 
then post-processed and evaluated for potential targets. In October of 2014 we 
positively identified the target of Project &#147;Sailfish,&#148; the Steamship 
<I>Connaught</I> via video and sonar imagery. &nbsp;We intend to return to the 
site of the <I>Connaught</I> in 2016 to recover its cargo. The cost of 
recovering the cargo of the <I>Connaught</I> is estimated to be $1,200,000. 
&nbsp;The Company needs additional working capital to recover the cargo of the 
<I>Connaught</I>. &nbsp;There can be no assurances that the Company will be 
successful in securing additional working capital and therefore cannot represent
it will ever be in position to recover the cargo of the <I>Connaught</I>.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In November 2013, Endurance LLC entered into
a contract with the sovereign government of an island nation in the Indian 
Ocean. The contract provides us with a three-year period in which to operate 
within the territorial waters of the nation with full permission to survey for 
and recover the <I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148;</I> and her silver cargo. &nbsp;We 
are currently pursuing an option to extend the existing contract. Net proceeds 
of our recovery efforts, after payment of the costs to transport, store and 
insure any recovered items, will be split between us (75%) and the island 
government (25%). &nbsp;The cost of finding and recovering the cargo of the 
<I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148;</I> is estimated to be $2,000,000. The Company needs
additional working capital to undertake the search for the <I>&#147;Black 
Marlin&#148;</I>. &nbsp;There can be no assurances that the Company will be 
successful in securing additional working capital and therefore cannot represent
it will ever be in position to search for and recover the cargo of the 
<I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148;</I>. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Results of Operations</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The following information represents our 
results of operations for the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 and 
2015</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>15</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<HR style="margin-bottom:9.6px; padding-top:9.6px" noshade size=1.333>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B><U>Three Months
Ended June 30, 2016 and 2015</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Revenue</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Since inception through June 30, 2016, we 
have not generated any revenues. &nbsp;However, during this period of time, the 
Company has acquired a ship, side scan sonar, topside computer processing of 
sonar images and a remotely operated vehicle with cameras that can visually 
inspect things located by the side scan sonar. &nbsp;The Company, through 
contracted personnel, has also developed an operational capability for this ship
and its equipment. &nbsp;The Company can also access, on a contract basis, 
additional ships, equipment and personnel on a case-by-case basis when needed. 
&nbsp;This capability allows the Company to offer aquatic research, survey, 
inspection and recovery, as well as maritime contract services and consulting to
both the public and private sectors that contract for such equipment and 
services. &nbsp;As of the time of this filing there are no agreement or 
contracts for the use of the Company equipment or the services described herein 
and the Company needs additional working capital to continue to offer said 
equipment and services. &nbsp;Therefore, the Company cannot represent that, in 
the future, it will ever generate revenue from aquatic research, survey, 
inspection and recovery projects, as well as maritime contract services and 
consulting.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Expenses</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We incurred operations and research expenses
of $11,138 for the three months ended June 30, 2016 as compared to $79,356 for 
the three months ended June 30, 2015, a decrease of $68,218. &nbsp;The primary 
reason for this three month net decrease is due to the decreased spending on 
salvage operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We incurred marketing and promotion expenses
of $2,511 for the three months ended June 30, 2016 as compared to $19,566 for 
the three months ended June 30, 2015, a decrease of $17,055. &nbsp;This decrease
is primarily due to an overall decrease in &nbsp;both advertising and printing 
expenses.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We incurred general and administrative 
expenses of $27,457 for the three months ended June 30, 2016 as compared to 
$63,648 for the three months ended June 30, 2015, a decrease of $36,491. 
&nbsp;This decrease in general and administrative costs is a result of decreased
operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Other Income (Expense)</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>For the three months ended June 30, 2016, 
other income (expense) consisted only of interest expense of ($1,121) as 
compared to the three months ended June 30, 2015 which had interest expense of 
($375) offset by other income from a gain on cancelation of debt in the amount 
of $63,144. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Net Losses</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>For the three months ended June 30, 2016, we
incurred a net loss of $67,848 as compared to a net loss of $125,569 for the 
three months ended June 30, 2015.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><U>Six Months Ended June 30, 2016 and 
2015</U></B></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Revenue</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Since inception through June 30, 2016, we 
have not generated any revenues. &nbsp;However, as stated above, during this 
period of time, the Company has acquired a ship, side scan sonar, topside 
computer processing of sonar images and a remotely operated vehicle with cameras
that can visually inspect things located by the side scan sonar. &nbsp;The 
Company, through contracted personnel, has also developed an operational 
capability for this ship and its equipment. &nbsp;The Company can also access, 
on a contract basis, additional ships, equipment and personnel on a case-by-case
basis when needed. &nbsp;This capability allows the Company to offer aquatic

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<A NAME="SUPER8KTECTONDJH2_HTM_PAGE_19"></A><P style="margin:0px" 
align=justify><B><I>Current Liquidity and Capital Resources</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Since inception, we have funded our 
operations through the sale of equity securities and advances made to us by our 
officers and directors and their affiliated entities. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>As of June 30, 2016, we had $5,920 in cash. 
&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Net cash used by operating activities was 
$104,030 for the six months ended June 30, 2016. &nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>There was no cash used by investing 
activities for the six months ended June 30, 2016.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Net cash provided by financing activities 
was $109,125 for the six months ended June 30, 2016, which consisted of advances
from related parties in the amount of $140,000 offset by $30,875 of deferred 
offering costs.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><U>Other Recent Financings</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During the six months ended June 30, 2016, 
Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC made net advances to the Company in the 
aggregate amount of $140,000, in order to provide the Company with funds to 
carry on its operations. &nbsp;These advances do not bear interest, are 
unsecured and have no specific terms of repayment. &nbsp;As of June 30, 2016, 
the aggregate amount of such advances outstanding was $235,500. Interest has not
been imputed on this balance as management has deemed it to be immaterial.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><U>Future Capital Requirements</U> </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our current available cash and cash 
equivalents are insufficient to satisfy our liquidity requirements. &nbsp;Our 
capital requirements for 2016 will depend on numerous factors, including 
management&#146;s evaluation of the timing of projects to pursue. Subject to our
ability to generate revenues and cash flow from operations and our ability to 
raise additional capital (including through possible joint ventures and/or 
partnerships), we expect to incur substantial expenditures to carry out our 
business plan, as well as costs associated with our capital raising efforts and 
being a public company. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>17</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<HR style="margin-bottom:9.6px; padding-top:9.6px" noshade size=1.333>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our plans to finance our operations include 
seeking equity and debt financing, alliances or other partnership agreements, or
other business transactions, that would generate sufficient resources to ensure 
continuation of our operations. &nbsp;. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The sale of additional equity or debt 
securities may result in additional dilution to our shareholders. If we raise 
additional funds through the issuance of debt securities or preferred stock, 
these securities could have rights senior to those of our common stock and could
contain covenants that would restrict our operations. &nbsp;Any such required 
additional capital may not be available on reasonable terms, if at all. If we 
were unable to obtain additional financing, we may be required to reduce the 
scope of, delay or eliminate some or all of our planned activities and limit our
operations which could have a material adverse effect on our business, financial
condition and results of operations. </P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Application of critical accounting 
policies</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of
our Financial Condition and Results of Operations is based on the Company&#146;s
audited Consolidated Financial Statements, which have been prepared in 
accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP). The 
preparation of financial statements in accordance with GAAP requires that we 
make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and 
liabilities and corresponding disclosures at the date of the financial 
statements, as well as the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the 
reporting period. On an ongoing basis, we continue to evaluate our estimates 
which in large part are based on historical experience and on various 
assumptions that we believe to be reasonable under the circumstances. The 
results of these estimates form the basis for making judgments about the 
carrying values of assets and liabilities that are not readily available from 
other sources. Actual results may differ from these estimates under different 
assumptions or conditions.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;<B><I>Inflation</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The amounts presented in the financial 
statements do not provide for the effect of inflation on our operations or 
financial position. The net operating losses shown would be greater than
reported if the effects of inflation were reflected either by charging 
operations with amounts that represent replacement costs or by using other 
inflation adjustments.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

Arrangements</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>As of June 30, 2016, we had no off balance 
sheet transactions that have or are reasonably likely to have a current or 
future effect on our financial condition, changes in our financial condition, 
revenues or expenses, results of operations, liquidity, capital expenditures or 
capital resources. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>18</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<A NAME="page_21"></A><P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT 
style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>ITEM 3. QUANTITATIVE AND QUALITATIVE 
DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Not 
applicable.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-
color:#FFFFFF"><B>ITEM 4. CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">As of
June 30, 2016, under the direction of our Chief Executive Officer and Chief 
Financial Officer, we evaluated the effectiveness of the design and operation of
our disclosure controls and procedures, as defined in Rule 15d-15(e) under the 
Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. &nbsp;Our disclosure controls and 
procedures are designed to provide reasonable assurance that the information 
required to be disclosed in our SEC reports is recorded, processed, summarized 
and reported within the time period specified by the SEC&#146;s rules and forms,
and is accumulated and communicated to management, including our Chief Executive
Officer and Chief Financial Officer, as appropriate to allow timely decisions 
regarding required disclosure. We concluded that, as of June 30, 2016, our 
disclosure controls and procedures were not effective at the reasonable 
assurance level.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">There
were no changes in our internal controls over financial reporting during the 
quarter ended June 30, 2016 that have materially affected, or are reasonably 
likely to materially affect, our internal controls over financial 
reporting.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><FONT style="background-
color:#FFFFFF"><B>PART II &#150; OTHER INFORMATION</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-
color:#FFFFFF"><B>ITEM 1. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">We 
are not a party to any legal proceedings, and we are not aware of any legal 
proceedings contemplated by any governmental authority against us. </FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-
color:#FFFFFF"><B>ITEM 1A. RISK FACTORS</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Not 
applicable.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-
color:#FFFFFF"><B>ITEM 2. UNREGISTERED SALES OF EQUITY SECURITIES AND USE OF 
PROCCEDS</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On February 12, 2015, we entered into a Debt
Conversion Agreement with Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC 
(&#147;Endeavour&#148;) relating to the conversion of indebtedness to Endeavour 
in the amount of $85,000. This amount represents the related party debt payable 
to Endeavour as of that date. &nbsp;The terms of the agreement allowed for 
Endeavour to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 per share. 
&nbsp;Endeavour converted all of such debt into shares, as a result of which we 
issued 340,000 shares to Endeavour. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On February 12, 2015, we entered into a Debt
Conversion Agreement with Micah Eldred relating to the conversion of 
indebtedness to Micah Eldred in the amount of $143,333. This amount represents 
the related party debt payable to Micah Eldred as of that date. &nbsp;The terms 
of the agreement allowed for Micah Eldred to convert this debt into common stock
at $0.25 per share. &nbsp;Micah Eldred converted all of such debt into shares, 
as a result of which we issued 573,333 shares to Micah Eldred. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On February 12, 2015, we entered into a Debt
Conversion Agreement with Carl &amp; Heather Dilley relating to the conversion 
of indebtedness to Carl &amp; Heather Dilley in the amount of $45,867 and 
$25,800 respectively. This amount represents the related party debt payable to 
Carl &amp; Heather Dilley as of that date. &nbsp;The terms of the agreement 
allowed for Carl &amp; Heather Dilley to convert this debt into common stock at 
$0.25 per share. &nbsp;Carl &amp; Heather Dilley converted all of such debt into
shares, as a result of which we issued 183,467 and 103,200 shares to Carl &amp; 
Heather Dilley respectively.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">During April 2015, the Company issued 600,000 common 
shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in fulfillment of stock 
subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">During May 2015, the Company issued 200,000 common shares 
at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in fulfillment of stock 
subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On May 15, 2015, the Company issued 
2,000,000 common shares to Eclipse Group, Inc. at $.25 per share as prepayment 
for certain salvage services pursuant to an agreement entered into on the same 
date. &nbsp;Steven Saint Amour, who serves as a member of our Board of 
Directors, and Joan Saint Amour are the principal shareholders and officers of 
Eclipse.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:'Arial'; font-size:11pt" align=center>19</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<HR style="margin-bottom:9.6px; padding-top:9.6px" noshade size=1.333>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">On June 29, 2015, the Company issued 8,184 common shares 
at $.25 per share for services.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During July 2015, the Company issued 200,000
common shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in fulfillment of 
stock subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During August 2015, the Company issued 
1,670,000 common shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in 
fulfillment of stock subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During September 2015, the Company issued
200,000 common shares at $.25 per share to non-affiliated investors in 
fulfillment of stock subscriptions received.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On September 30, 2015, the Company issued 
167,725 common shares at $.25 per share for services.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During November 2015, the Company issued 
149,600 common shares at $.25 per share for services</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>All of the foregoing shares were issued in 
transactions exempt from registration under Section 4(a)(2) of the Securities 
Act of 1933. &nbsp;</P>

<us-gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;b&gt;NOTE A - SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING 
POLICIES&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;A summary of the significant 
accounting policies applied in the preparation of the accompanying consolidated 
financial statements follows.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Description of 
Business&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;Endurance Exploration Group, Inc. 
(formerly Tecton Corporation) (the &amp;#147;Company&amp;#148;) was incorporated
under the laws of the State of Nevada on January 19, 2006, as a wholly-owned 
subsidiary of Hemis Corporation.&amp;#160; On December 1, 2006 Hemis declared a 
dividend of Tecton shares to all shareholders as of that date and concurrently 
cancelled its share ownership in the Company.&amp;#160; The effect of this 
dividend declaration and share cancellation was that Tecton was spun off as an 
independent company.&amp;#160; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On 
November 8, 2013, the Board of Directors approved a change of the 
Company&amp;#146;s fiscal year from January 31, to December 
31.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On December 31, 2013, the Company 
acquired 100% of the membership interests of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC 
(&amp;#147;Endurance LLC&amp;#148;), a Florida limited liability company, in 
exchange for 20,550,539 shares of the Company&amp;#146;s Common Stock being 
issued to the former members. Endurance LLC is now a wholly owned subsidiary 
with its operations being the Company&amp;#146;s primary focus.&amp;#160; 
&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Endurance Exploration Group LLC&lt;/u&gt; 
&amp;#150; is engaged in the archaeologically sensitive exploration and recovery
of deep-ocean shipwrecks throughout the world. We intend to recover bullion 
precious metals, numismatic-grade coinage, high-value non-ferrous metals and 
other valuable cargos from both historic and modern shipwrecks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On January 2, 2014, the Company 
changed its name to Endurance Exploration Group, Inc.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;Our corporate headquarters are 
located in Clearwater, Florida.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Principles of consolidation and basis of 
presentation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;These consolidated financial 
statements include the assets and liabilities of the Endurance Exploration 
Group, Inc. (formerly Tecton Corporation) and its subsidiaries as of June 30, 
2016.&amp;#160; The acquisition of the membership interests of Endurance LLC and
its wholly owned Panamanian subsidiary formed to hold the registry of a research
vessel occurred as of the close of its business on December 31, 2013.&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The unaudited interim consolidated 
financial statements have been prepared pursuant to the rules and regulations of
the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (the 
&amp;#147;SEC&amp;#148;).&amp;#160; Certain information and footnote disclosures
normally included in annual financial statements prepared in accordance with 
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States have been 
condensed or omitted pursuant to such SEC rules and regulations, although the 
Company believes that the disclosures made are adequate to make the information 
not misleading. It is suggested that these consolidated financial statements be 
read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and the notes 
thereto, included in the Company&amp;#146;s latest Annual Report on Form 10-
K.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;In the opinion of management, all 
adjustments consisting of normal recurring adjustments necessary for a fair 
statement of the financial position at June 30, 2016 and the results of 
operations for the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 and cash 
flows for the six months ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 have been made.&amp;#160; 
All material intercompany transactions have been eliminated.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Use of 
Estimates&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The preparation of financial 
statements in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles 
requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported 
amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and 
liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of 
revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Actual results could differ 
from those estimates.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Subsequent Events&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none&apos;&gt;The Company has evaluated subsequent events through the 
filing of this Form 10-Q, to assess the need for potential recognition or 
disclosure in this report. Based upon this evaluation, management determined 
that all subsequent events that require recognition in the financial statements 
have been included.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;text-autospace:none&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cash and Cash 
Equivalents&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;For purposes of the Statements of 
Cash Flows, the Company considers all highly liquid debt instruments purchased 
with a maturity date of three months or less to be cash equivalents. &lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Offering 
Costs&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;As of June 30, 2016, the Company has 
incurred $30,875 of deferred offering costs associated with the planned sale of 
securities.&amp;#160; This amount is included on the balance sheet in prepaid 
expenses and deferred costs.&amp;#160; These costs will be netted against 
proceeds upon completion of the offering, or they will be expensed if the 
offering is unsuccessful.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;
 &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Fixed 
Assets&lt;/u&gt;&lt;b&gt; &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;Fixed assets are stated at historical
cost. Depreciation is provided using the straight-line method at rates based on 
the assets&amp;#146; estimated useful lives which are normally between three and
ten years. &amp;#160;When retired or otherwise disposed, the related carrying 
value and accumulated depreciation are removed from the respective accounts and 
the net difference less any amount realized from disposition, is reflected in 
earnings. Leasehold improvements are amortized over their estimated useful lives
or lease term, if shorter. Equipment and major overhaul items (such as engines 
or generators) that enhance or extend the useful life of vessel related assets 
qualify to be capitalized and depreciated over the useful life or remaining life
of that asset, whichever is shorter. Certain major repair items required by 
industry standards to ensure a vessel&amp;#146;s seaworthiness also qualify to 
be capitalized and depreciated over the period of time until the next scheduled 
planned major maintenance for that item. All other repairs and maintenance are 
accounted for under the direct-expensing method and are expensed when incurred. 
&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Impairment of Long-Lived 
Assets&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The 
Company reviews long-lived assets for impairment whenever events or changes in 
circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of such assets may not be 
recoverable.&amp;#160; Fair value is determined based on discounted cash flows 
or appraised values, depending on the nature of the assets. As of June 30, 2016 
and 2015, there were no impairment losses recognized for long-lived 
assets.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Income Taxes&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;The Company uses the liability method to
record income tax activity. Deferred taxes are determined based upon the 
estimated future tax effects of differences between the financial reporting and 
tax reporting bases of assets and liabilities given the provisions of currently 
enacted tax laws.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;The accounting for uncertainty in income taxes recognized
in an enterprise&amp;#146;s financial statements uses the threshold of more-
likely-than-not to be sustained upon examination for inclusion or exclusion. 
Measurement of the tax uncertainty occurs if the recognition threshold has been 
met. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Net Earnings (Losses) Per Common
Share&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The Company computes earnings (loss) 
per share by dividing net earnings (loss) by the weighted average number of 
shares of common stock and dilutive common stock equivalents outstanding during 
the year. Dilutive common stock equivalents may&amp;nbsp;consist of shares 
issuable upon conversion of convertible preferred shares and the exercise of the
Company&apos;s stock options (calculated using the treasury stock 
method).&amp;#160; As of June 30, 2016, there were 5,574,000 common stock 
equivalents that were anti-dilutive and were not included in the calculation. 
Common stock issuable is considered outstanding as of the original approval date
for purposes of earnings per share computations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Fair Value of Financial 
Instruments&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The fair value of financial 
instruments, which include cash, loans receivable, accounts payable and accrued 
expenses and advances from related parties were estimated to approximate their 
carrying values due to the immediate or short-term maturity of these financial 
instruments. Management is of the opinion that the Company is not exposed to 
significant interest, currency or credit risks arising from financial 
instruments.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Comprehensive 
Income&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;The Company records comprehensive income
as the change in equity of a business during a period from transactions and 
other events and circumstances from non-owner sources. It includes all changes 
in equity during a period except those resulting from investments by owners and 
distributions to owners. Other comprehensive income (loss) includes foreign 
currency translation adjustments and unrealized gains and losses on available-
for-sale securities. As of June 30, 2016 the Company had no items that represent
comprehensive loss and, therefore, has not included a schedule of comprehensive 
loss in the financial statements.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Stock Based 
Compensation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;Stock based compensation costs are 
measured at fair value on date of grant and recognition of compensation over the
service period for awards expected to vest. The Company determines the fair 
value of awards using the Black-Scholes valuation model. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;New Accounting 
Pronouncements&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The Company reviews new accounting 
standards as issued. No new standards had any material effect on these financial
statements. The accounting pronouncements issued subsequent to the date of these
financial statements that were considered significant by management were 
evaluated for the potential effect on these consolidated financial statements. 
Management does not believe any of the subsequent pronouncements will have a 
material effect on these consolidated financial statements as presented and does
not anticipate the need for any future restatement of these consolidated 
financial statements because of the retro-active application of any accounting 
pronouncements issued subsequent to June 30, 2016 through the date these 
financial statements were issued.&lt;/p&gt; </us-

<us-gaap:SubstantialDoubtAboutGoingConcernTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;b&gt;NOTE B &amp;#150; GOING CONCERN 
MATTERS&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The accompanying financial statements
have been prepared on a going concern basis, which contemplates the realization 
of assets and the satisfaction of liabilities in the normal course of business. 
As shown in the accompanying financial statements for the period January 19, 
2006 (date of inception) to June 30, 2016, the Company incurred losses of 
$6,745,493. The Company has minimal liquid assets. These factors, among others, 
indicate that the Company will be unable to continue as a going concern for a 
reasonable period of time.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The 
Company&apos;s existence is dependent upon management&apos;s ability to develop 
profitable operations and resolve its liquidity problems. The accompanying 
financial statements do not include any adjustments that might result should the
Company be unable to continue as a going concern.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:SubstantialDoubtAboutGoingConcernTextBlock>

controlling interests in both entities both before and after the 
transaction.&amp;#160; Accordingly, the acquisition has been accounted for as a 
corporate reorganization because of the common control.&amp;#160; The book value
of Endurance LLC at the time of the acquisition was as follows:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p

<us-gaap:OtherCurrentAssetsTextBlock contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--
egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;b&gt;NOTE D 
&amp;#150; PREPAID EXPENSES AND DEFERRED COSTS&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On May 
15, 2015, the Company entered into an agreement with Eclipse Group, Inc. to 
provide services, equipment and/or personnel in support of anticipated Endurance
salvage projects, to inspect and recover one or more shipwreck cargoes located 
by Endurance.&amp;#160; The Company issued 2,000,000 common shares at $.25 per 
share with a value of $500,000.&amp;#160; These shares represent a prepayment 
for Eclipse services pursuant to a schedule of agreed upon costs and 
rates.&amp;#160; Eclipse will invoice the Company on a monthly basis as services
are rendered.&amp;#160; During the year ended December 31, 2015, Eclipse 
rendered $150,000 of the services outlined in this agreement.&amp;#160; As of 
June 30, 2016, the Company has not received any additional invoices for services
outlined in this agreement, and consequently the remaining balance of $350,000 
is included in prepaid expenses along with $30,875 of deferred issuance costs 
for a total of $380,875 at June 30, 2016.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
