&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;/table&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;On December 31, 
2013, the Company completed the purchase of 100% of the membership interests of 
Endurance Exploration Group, LLC (&amp;#147;Endurance LLC&amp;#148;), from its 
members, Micah Eldred and Carl Dilley, in exchange for 20,550,539 shares of the 
Company&amp;#146;s common stock, valued at $0.0186 per share, based upon the net
book value of the assets of Endurance LLC, $381,173 as of December 31, 
2013.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;On December 31, 2013, as a consequence 
of acquiring the membership interests of Endurance LLC, the Company assumed a 
liability of Endurance LLC to Micah Eldred under a demand promissory note, dated
June 19, 2012, in the original principal amount of $60,000, bearing interest at 
5%.&amp;#160; The note has no stipulated maturity date, and the balance due 
under the note at June 30, 2016, including accrued interest, was 
$72,909.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;The Company has entered into a contract 
with Island Capital Management, LLC, which is related through common 
shareholders, to serve as its transfer agent.&amp;#160; It did not charge the 
Company for its services during the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 or 
2015, as management has deemed it to be immaterial.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;The Company has entered into a contract 
with Proxy &amp;amp; Printing, LLC, which is related through common 
shareholders, to provide the Company with printing and other services relating 
to its filings with the SEC.&amp;#160; It did not charge the Company for its 
services during the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 or 2015, as 
management has deemed it to be immaterial.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;On June 23, 2014, the Company entered 
into a contract with Eclipse Group Inc. (&amp;#147;Eclipse&amp;#148;) for 
Eclipse to provide personnel and services to the Company in connection with the 
operation and monitoring of a remotely operated vehicle 
(&amp;#147;ROV&amp;#148;) in connection with our investigation of a suspected 
shipwreck located off the coast of New England. Steven Saint Amour, who serves 
as a member of the Company&amp;#146;s Board of Directors, and Joan Saint Amour 
are the principal shareholders and officers of Eclipse.&amp;#160; The contract 
provides that Eclipse will provide 2 people, including Mr. Saint Amour, for 
approximately four 12-hour days to operate and monitor the ROV, which will be 
provided by the Company.&amp;#160; The Company will issue 100,000 shares of 
common stock to Mr. Saint Amour, with an agreed value of $25,000, under the 
contract, and reimburse Eclipse in cash for its cost for the second ROV 
technician.&amp;#160; The Company will also pay Eclipse in cash its cost plus 
15% for all third party costs incurred by Eclipse, and provide Mr. Saint Amour 
and the second technician with food and lodging during the assignment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On 
September 3, 2014, the Company entered into a contract with Overseas Marine 
Vessel Corp, LLC (&amp;#147;OMVC&amp;#148;) pursuant to which it will provide 
the Marine Vessel Manisee in support of an estimated 10-day mission to 
investigate, identify and recovery artifacts from one or more shipwrecks located
in our search area off the coast of New England.&amp;#160; We will reimburse 
OMVC in cash for all its out-of-pocket expenses only, including but not limited 
to, mooring, food, fuel, lube, satellite communications and crew 
costs.&amp;#160; Toni Eldred, the spouse of Micah Eldred, is a fifty percent 
owner of OMVC, and Micah Eldred is the co-manager of OMVC. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-autospace:none&apos;&gt;On February 12, 
2015, the Company entered into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Endeavour 
Cooperative Partners, LLC (&amp;#147;Endeavour&amp;#148;) relating to the 
conversion of indebtedness to Endeavour in the amount of $85,000. This amount 
represents the related party debt payable to Endeavour as of that 
date.&amp;#160; The terms of the agreement allowed for Endeavour to convert this
debt into common stock at $0.25 per share.&amp;#160; Endeavour converted all of 
such debt into shares, as a result of which we issued 340,000 shares to 
Endeavour.&amp;#160; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none&apos;&gt;On February 12, 2015, the Company entered into a Debt 
Conversion Agreement with Micah Eldred relating to the conversion of 
indebtedness to Micah Eldred in the amount of $143,333. This amount represents 
the related party debt payable to Micah Eldred as of that date.&amp;#160; The 
terms of the agreement allowed for Micah Eldred to convert this debt into common
stock at $0.25 per share.&amp;#160; Micah Eldred converted all of such debt into
shares, as a result of which we issued 573,333 shares to Micah Eldred. 
&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-autospace:none&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On 
February 12, 2015, the Company entered into a Debt Conversion Agreement
 with Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley relating to the conversion of indebtedness
to Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley in the amount of $45,867 and $25,800 
respectively. This amount represents the related party debt payable to Carl 
&amp;amp; Heather Dilley as of that date.&amp;#160; The terms of the agreement 
allowed for Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley to convert this debt into common stock
at $0.25 per share.&amp;#160; Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley converted all of 
such debt into shares, as a result of which we issued 183,467 and 103,200 shares
to Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley respectively.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;During the six months ended June 30, 
2016, Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC made net advances to the Company in 
the aggregate amount of $140,000, in order to provide the Company with funds to 
carry on its operations. &amp;#160;These advances do not bear interest, are 
unsecured and have no specific terms of repayment.&amp;#160; As of June 30, 
2016, the aggregate amount of such advances outstanding was $235,500. Interest 
has not been imputed on this balance as management has deemed it to be 
immaterial.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:RelatedPartyTransactionsDisclosureTextBlock>
<fil:PreferredAndCommonStockTransactionsAndReverseSplitDisclosureTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&lt;b&gt;NOTE G 
&amp;#150; PREFERRED AND COMMON STOCK TRANSACTIONS AND REVERSE 
SPLIT&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none&apos;&gt;On February 12, 2015, the Company entered into a Debt 
Conversion Agreement with Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC 
(&amp;#147;Endeavour&amp;#148;) relating to the conversion of indebtedness to 
Endeavour in the amount of $85,000. This amount represents the related party 
debt payable to Endeavour as of that date.&amp;#160; The terms of the agreement 
allowed for Endeavour to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 per 
share.&amp;#160; Endeavour converted all of such debt into shares, as a result 
of which we issued 340,000 shares to Endeavour.&amp;#160; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none&apos;&gt;On February 12, 2015, the Company entered into a Debt 
Conversion Agreement with Micah Eldred relating to the conversion of 
indebtedness to Micah Eldred in the amount of $143,333. This amount represents 
the related party debt payable to Micah Eldred as of that date.&amp;#160; The 
terms of the agreement allowed for Micah Eldred to convert this debt into common
stock at $0.25 per share.&amp;#160; Micah Eldred converted all of such debt into
shares, as a result of which we issued 573,333 shares to Micah Eldred. 
&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-autospace:none&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;On February 12, 2015, the Company 
entered into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley 
relating to the conversion of indebtedness to Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley in 
the amount of $45,867 and $25,800 respectively. This amount represents the 
related party debt payable to Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley as of that 
date.&amp;#160; The terms of the agreement allowed for Carl &amp;amp; Heather 
Dilley to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 per share.&amp;#160; Carl
&amp;amp; Heather Dilley converted all of such debt into shares, as a result of 
which we issued 183,467 and 103,200 shares to Carl &amp;amp; Heather Dilley 
respectively.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;During 
April 2015, the Company issued 600,000 common shares at $.25 per share to non-
affiliated investors in fulfillment of stock subscriptions received.&lt;/p&gt;

align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-

serves as a member of our Board of Directors, and Joan Saint Amour are the

egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;b&gt;NOTE I 
&amp;#150; INCOME TAXES&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;There is no current or deferred 
income tax expense or benefit allocated to continuing operations for the period 
ended June 30, 2016 and 2015. The Company has not recognized an income tax 
benefit for its operating losses generated through June 30, 2016 based on 
uncertainties concerning the Company&amp;#146;s ability to generate taxable 
income in future periods.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The tax benefit is offset by a 
valuation allowance established against deferred tax assets arising from 
operating losses and other temporary differences, the realization of which could
not be considered more likely than not.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In future periods, 
tax benefits and related deferred tax assets will be recognized when management 
considers realization of such amounts to be more likely than not.&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;For income tax purposes the Company 
has available a net operating loss carry-forward of approximately $6,745,000 
from inception to June 30, 2016, which will expire, unless used to offset future
federal taxable income beginning in 2024.&amp;#160; The tax years ending 
December 31, 2013 through December 31, 2014 are open for inspection by both 
Federal and State Agencies.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:IncomeTaxDisclosureTextBlock>

<us-gaap:NatureOfOperations contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--
&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Description 
of Business&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;Endurance Exploration Group, Inc. 
(formerly Tecton Corporation) (the &amp;#147;Company&amp;#148;) was incorporated
under the laws of the State of Nevada on January 19, 2006, as a wholly-owned 
subsidiary of Hemis Corporation.&amp;#160; On December 1, 2006 Hemis declared a 
dividend of Tecton shares to all shareholders as of that date and concurrently 
cancelled its share ownership in the Company.&amp;#160; The effect of this 
dividend declaration and share cancellation was that Tecton was spun off as an 
independent company.&amp;#160; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On 
November 8, 2013, the Board of Directors approved a change of the 
Company&amp;#146;s fiscal year from January 31, to December 
31.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On December 31, 2013, the Company 
acquired 100% of the membership interests of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC 
(&amp;#147;Endurance LLC&amp;#148;), a Florida limited liability company, in 
exchange for 20,550,539 shares of the Company&amp;#146;s Common Stock being 
issued to the former members. Endurance LLC is now a wholly owned subsidiary 
with its operations being the Company&amp;#146;s primary focus.&amp;#160; 
&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Endurance Exploration Group LLC&lt;/u&gt; 
&amp;#150; is engaged in the archaeologically sensitive exploration and recovery
of deep-ocean shipwrecks throughout the world. We intend to recover bullion 
precious metals, numismatic-grade coinage, high-value non-ferrous metals and 
other valuable cargos from both historic and modern shipwrecks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;On January 2, 2014, the Company 
changed its name to Endurance Exploration Group, Inc.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;Our corporate headquarters are 
located in Clearwater, Florida.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:NatureOfOperations>
<us-gaap:ConsolidationPolicyTextBlock contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--
egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Principles 
of consolidation and basis of presentation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;These 
consolidated financial statements include the assets and liabilities of the 
Endurance Exploration Group, Inc. (formerly Tecton Corporation) and its 
subsidiaries as of June 30, 2016.&amp;#160; The acquisition of the membership 
interests of Endurance LLC and its wholly owned Panamanian subsidiary formed to 
hold the registry of a research vessel occurred as of the close of its business 
on December 31, 2013.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The 
unaudited interim consolidated financial statements have been prepared pursuant 
to the rules and regulations of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (the
&amp;#147;SEC&amp;#148;).&amp;#160; Certain information and footnote disclosures
normally included in annual financial statements prepared in accordance with 
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States have been 
condensed or omitted pursuant to such SEC rules and regulations, although the 
Company believes that the disclosures made are adequate to make the information 
not misleading. It is suggested that these consolidated financial statements be 
read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and the notes 
thereto, included in the Company&amp;#146;s latest Annual Report on Form 10-
K.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;In the opinion of management, all 
adjustments consisting of normal recurring adjustments necessary for a fair 
statement of the financial position at June 30, 2016 and the results of 
operations for the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 and cash 
flows for the six months ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 have been made.&amp;#160; 
All material intercompany transactions have been eliminated.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ConsolidationPolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:UseOfEstimates contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Use of 
Estimates&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The preparation of financial 
statements in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles 
requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported 
amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and 
liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of 
revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Actual results could differ 
from those estimates.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:UseOfEstimates>
<us-gaap:SubsequentEventsPolicyPolicyTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;

align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Subsequent Events&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none&apos;&gt;The Company has evaluated subsequent events through the 
filing of this Form 10-Q, to assess the need for potential recognition or 
disclosure in this report. Based upon this evaluation, management determined 
that all subsequent events that require recognition in the financial statements 
have been included.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:SubsequentEventsPolicyPolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:CashAndCashEquivalentsPolicyTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cash and Cash Equivalents&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;For 
purposes of the Statements of Cash Flows, the Company considers all highly 
liquid debt instruments purchased with a maturity date of three months or less 
to be cash equivalents. &lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:CashAndCashEquivalentsPolicyTextBlock>
<fil:OfferingCostsPolicyTextBlock contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--
&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Offering 
Costs&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;As of June 30, 2016, the Company has 
incurred $30,875 of deferred offering costs associated with the planned sale of 
securities.&amp;#160; This amount is included on the balance sheet in prepaid 
expenses and deferred costs.&amp;#160; These costs will be netted against 
proceeds upon completion of the offering, or they will be expensed if the 
offering is unsuccessful.&lt;/p&gt;</fil:OfferingCostsPolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:PropertyPlantAndEquipmentPolicyTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Fixed Assets&lt;/u&gt;&lt;b&gt; 
&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;Fixed assets are stated at historical cost. Depreciation
is provided using the straight-line method at rates based on the 
assets&amp;#146; estimated useful lives which are normally between three and ten
years. &amp;#160;When retired or otherwise disposed, the related carrying value 
and accumulated depreciation are removed from the respective accounts and the 
net difference less any amount realized from disposition, is reflected in 
earnings. Leasehold improvements are amortized over their estimated useful lives
or lease term, if shorter. Equipment and major overhaul items (such as engines 
or generators) that enhance or extend the useful life of vessel related assets 
qualify to be capitalized and depreciated over the useful life or remaining life
of that asset, whichever is shorter. Certain major repair items required by 
industry standards to ensure a vessel&amp;#146;s seaworthiness also qualify to 
be capitalized and depreciated over the period of time until the next scheduled 
planned major maintenance for that item. All other repairs and maintenance are 
accounted for under the direct-expensing method and are expensed when incurred. 
&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:PropertyPlantAndEquipmentPolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:ImpairmentOrDisposalOfLongLivedAssetsPolicyTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Impairment of Long-Lived Assets&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The Company reviews long-lived assets
for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the 
carrying amount of such assets may not be recoverable.&amp;#160; Fair value is 
determined based on discounted cash flows or appraised values, depending on the 
nature of the assets. As of June 30, 2016 and 2015, there were no impairment 
losses recognized for long-lived assets.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ImpairmentOrDisposalOfLongLivedAssetsPolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:IncomeTaxPolicyTextBlock contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--
&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Income 
Taxes&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;The Company uses the
liability method to record income tax activity. Deferred taxes are determined 
based upon the estimated future tax effects of differences between the financial
reporting and tax reporting bases of assets and liabilities given the provisions
of currently enacted tax laws.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify&apos;&gt;The accounting for uncertainty in income taxes recognized
in an enterprise&amp;#146;s financial statements uses the threshold of more-
likely-than-not to be sustained upon examination for inclusion or exclusion. 
Measurement of the tax uncertainty occurs if the recognition threshold has been 
met. &lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:IncomeTaxPolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:EarningsPerSharePolicyTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Net Earnings (Losses) Per Common 
Share&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The Company computes earnings (loss) 
per share by dividing net earnings (loss) by the weighted average number of 
shares of common stock and dilutive common stock equivalents outstanding during 
the year. Dilutive common stock equivalents may&amp;nbsp;consist of shares 
issuable upon conversion of convertible preferred shares and the exercise of the
Company&apos;s stock options (calculated using the treasury stock 
method).&amp;#160; As of June 30, 2016, there were 5,574,000 common stock 
equivalents that were anti-dilutive and were not included in the calculation. 
Common stock issuable is considered outstanding as of the original approval date
for purposes of earnings per share computations.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:EarningsPerSharePolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:FairValueOfFinancialInstrumentsPolicy
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Fair Value of Financial 
Instruments&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The fair value of financial 
instruments, which include cash, loans receivable, accounts payable and accrued 
expenses and advances from related parties were estimated to approximate their 
carrying values due to the immediate or short-term maturity of these financial 
instruments. Management is of the opinion that the Company is not exposed to 
significant interest, currency or credit risks arising from financial 
instruments.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:FairValueOfFinancialInstrumentsPolicy>
<us-gaap:ComprehensiveIncomePolicyPolicyTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Comprehensive 
Income&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;The Company records comprehensive income
as the change in equity of a business during a period from transactions and 
other events and circumstances from non-owner sources. It includes all changes 
in equity during a period except those resulting from investments by owners and 
distributions to owners. Other comprehensive income (loss) includes foreign 
currency translation adjustments and unrealized gains and losses on available-
for-sale securities. As of June 30, 2016 the Company had no items that represent
comprehensive loss and, therefore, has not included a schedule of comprehensive 
loss in the financial statements.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ComprehensiveIncomePolicyPolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:CompensationRelatedCostsPolicyTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Stock Based 
Compensation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white&apos;&gt;Stock based compensation costs are 
measured at fair value on date of grant and recognition of compensation over the
service period for awards expected to vest. The Company determines the fair 
value of awards using the Black-Scholes valuation model. &lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:CompensationRelatedCostsPolicyTextBlock>
<us-gaap:NewAccountingPronouncementsPolicyPolicyTextBlock
contextRef='D160101_160630'>&lt;!--egx--&gt;&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;

align:left&apos;&gt;&lt;u&gt;New Accounting Pronouncements&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot; style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left&apos;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p 
style=&apos;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify&apos;&gt;The 
Company reviews new accounting standards as issued. No new standards had any 
material effect on these financial statements. The accounting pronouncements 
issued subsequent to the date of these financial statements that were considered
significant by management were evaluated for the potential effect on these 
consolidated financial statements. Management does not believe any of the 
subsequent pronouncements will have a material effect on these consolidated 
financial statements as presented and does not anticipate the need for any 
future restatement of these consolidated financial statements because of the 
retro-active application of any accounting pronouncements issued subsequent to 
June 30, 2016 through the date these financial statements were 
issued.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:NewAccountingPronouncementsPolicyPolicyTextBlock>

<P style="margin:0px">In connection with the Quarterly Report of Endurance 
Exploration Group, Inc. (the &#147;Company&#148;) on Form 10-Q for the period 
ended June 30, 2016, as filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission on the
date hereof (the &#147;report&#148;), I, Micah Eldred, Chief Executive Officer 
of the registrant, and I, Christine Zitman, Chief Financial Officer of the 
registrant, certify, pursuant to 18&nbsp;U.S.C.&nbsp;&#167;&nbsp;1350, that:</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">(1) The report fully complies with the requirements of 
section 13(a) or 15(d) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended; 
and</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">(2) The information contained in the report fairly 
presents, in all material respects, the financial condition and results of

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData" 
style="display: none;" id="defref_us-gaap_AdditionalPaidInCapital">
<tr><td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td></tr>
<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>Excess of issue price over par or stated value of the 
entity's capital stock and amounts received from other transactions involving 
the entity's stock or stockholders. Includes adjustments to additional paid in 
capital. Some examples of such adjustments include recording the issuance of 
debt with a beneficial conversion feature and certain tax consequences of equity
instruments awarded to employees. Use this element for the aggregate amount of 
additional paid-in capital associated with common and preferred stock. For 
additional paid-in capital associated with only common stock, use the element 
additional paid in capital, common stock. For additional paid-in capital 
associated with only preferred stock, use the element additional paid in 
capital, preferred stock.</p></div>
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ 
References</a><div style="display: none;"><p>Reference 1:

<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>Amount of currency on hand as well as demand deposits with
banks or financial institutions. Includes other kinds of accounts that have the 
general characteristics of demand deposits. Also includes short-term, highly 
liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash 
and so near their maturity that they present insignificant risk of changes in 
value because of changes in interest rates. Excludes cash and cash equivalents 
within disposal group and discontinued operation.</p></div>

amortization of physical assets used in the normal conduct of business to 
produce goods and services and not intended for resale. Examples include, but 
are not limited to, land, buildings, machinery and equipment, office equipment, 
and furniture and fixtures.</p></div>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData"

<tr><td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);"

<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>Total of all stockholders' equity (deficit) items, net of 
receivables from officers, directors, owners, and affiliates of the entity which
are attributable to the parent. The amount of the economic entity's 
stockholders' equity attributable to the parent excludes the amount of 
stockholders' equity which is allocable to that ownership interest in subsidiary
equity which is not attributable to the parent (noncontrolling interest, 
minority interest). This excludes temporary equity and is sometimes called 
permanent equity.</p></div>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData" 
style="display: none;" id="defref_us-gaap_EarningsPerShareBasicAndDiluted">
<tr><td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td></tr>
<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>The amount of net income or loss for the period per each 
share in instances when basic and diluted earnings per share are the same amount
and reported as a single line item on the face of the financial statements.  
Basic earnings per share is the amount of net income or loss for the period per 
each share of common stock or unit outstanding during the reporting period.  
Diluted earnings per share includes the amount of net income or loss for the 
period available to each share of common stock or common unit outstanding during
the reporting period and to each share or unit that would have been outstanding 
assuming the issuance of common shares or units for all dilutive potential 
common shares or units outstanding during the reporting period.</p></div>
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ 
References</a><div style="display: none;"><p>No definition available.</p></div>
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ 
Details</a><div style="display: none;"><table border="0" cellpadding="0" 
cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td><strong> Name:</strong></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;">us-gaap_EarningsPerShareBasicAndDiluted</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="padding-right: 4px;white-space:nowrap;"><strong> Namespace 
Prefix:</strong></td>
<td>us-gaap_</td>
</tr>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData" 
style="display: none;" id="defref_us-gaap_ResearchAndDevelopmentExpense">
<tr><td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td></tr>
<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>The aggregate costs incurred (1) in a planned search or 
critical investigation aimed at discovery of new knowledge with the hope that 
such knowledge will be useful in developing a new product or service, a new 
process or technique, or in bringing about a significant improvement to an 
existing product or process; or (2) to translate research findings or other 
knowledge into a plan or design for a new product or process or for a 
significant improvement to an existing product or process whether intended for 
sale or the entity's use, during the reporting period charged to research and 
development projects, including the costs of developing computer software up to 
the point in time of achieving technological feasibility, and costs allocated in
accounting for a business combination to in-process projects deemed to have no 
alternative future use.</p></div>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData" 
style="display: none;" id="defref_us-
gaap_CashAndCashEquivalentsAtCarryingValue">
<tr><td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td></tr>
<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>Amount of currency on hand as well as demand deposits with
banks or financial institutions. Includes other kinds of accounts that have the 
general characteristics of demand deposits. Also includes short-term, highly 
liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash 
and so near their maturity that they present insignificant risk of changes in 
value because of changes in interest rates. Excludes cash and cash equivalents 
within disposal group and discontinued operation.</p></div>

Definition</a><div><p>Total number of common shares of an entity that have been 
sold or granted to shareholders (includes common shares that were issued, 
repurchased and remain in the treasury). These shares represent capital invested
by the firm's shareholders and owners, and may be all or only a portion of the 
number of shares authorized. Shares issued include shares outstanding and shares
held in the treasury.</p></div>

Definition</a><div><p>The increase (decrease) during the reporting period in the
aggregate amount of obligations to be paid to the following types of related 
parties: a parent company and its subsidiaries; subsidiaries of a common parent;
an entity and trust for the benefit of employees, such as pension and profit-
sharing trusts that are managed by or under the trusteeship of the entities' 
management; an entity and its principal owners, management, or member of their 
immediate families, affiliates, or other parties with the ability to exert 
significant influence.</p></div>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData"
style="display: none;" id="defref_us-
gaap_NetCashProvidedByUsedInFinancingActivities">
<tr><td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td></tr>
<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>Amount of cash inflow (outflow) from financing activities,
including discontinued operations. Financing activity cash flows include 
obtaining resources from owners and providing them with a return on, and a 
return of, their investment; borrowing money and repaying amounts borrowed, or 
settling the obligation; and obtaining and paying for other resources obtained 
from creditors on long-term credit.</p></div>
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ 
References</a><div style="display: none;"><p>Reference 1:

<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>Amount of cash inflow (outflow) from investing activities,
including discontinued operations. Investing activity cash flows include making 
and collecting loans and acquiring and disposing of debt or equity instruments 
and property, plant, and equipment and other productive assets.</p></div>

<tr>
<th class="tl" colspan="1" rowspan="2"><div style="width: 200px;"><strong>Note A
- Summary of Significant Accounting Policies<br></strong></div></th>
<th class="th" colspan="1">6 Months Ended</th>
</tr>
<tr><th class="th"><div>Jun. 30, 2016</div></th></tr>
<tr class="re">
<td class="pl " style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_DisclosureTextBlockAbstract', window );"><strong>Notes</strong></a></td>
<td class="text">&#160;<span></span>
</td>
</tr>
<tr class="ro">
<td class="pl " style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock', window );">Note A - Summary of 
Significant Accounting Policies</a></td>
<td class="text"><!--egx--><p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><b>NOTE A - SUMMARY OF 
SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES</b></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>A summary of the significant accounting policies applied in the 
preparation of the accompanying consolidated financial statements follows.</p> 
<p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'><u>Description of Business</u></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>Endurance Exploration Group, Inc. (formerly Tecton Corporation) 
(the &#147;Company&#148;) was incorporated under the laws of the State of Nevada
on January 19, 2006, as a wholly-owned subsidiary of Hemis Corporation.&#160; On
December 1, 2006 Hemis declared a dividend of Tecton shares to all shareholders 
as of that date and concurrently cancelled its share ownership in the
Company.&#160; The effect of this dividend declaration and share cancellation 
was that Tecton was spun off as an independent company.&#160; </p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>On November 8, 2013,
the Board of Directors approved a change of the Company&#146;s fiscal year from 
January 31, to December 31.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>On December 31, 
2013, the Company acquired 100% of the membership interests of Endurance 
Exploration Group, LLC (&#147;Endurance LLC&#148;), a Florida limited liability 
company, in exchange for 20,550,539 shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock 
being issued to the former members. Endurance LLC is now a wholly owned 
subsidiary with its operations being the Company&#146;s primary focus.&#160; 
</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'><u>Endurance Exploration Group LLC</u> &#150;
is engaged in the archaeologically sensitive exploration and recovery of deep-
ocean shipwrecks throughout the world. We intend to recover bullion precious 
metals, numismatic-grade coinage, high-value non-ferrous metals and other 
valuable cargos from both historic and modern shipwrecks.</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>On January 2, 2014, 
the Company changed its name to Endurance Exploration Group, Inc.</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>Our corporate 
headquarters are located in Clearwater, Florida.</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><u>Principles of 
consolidation and basis of presentation</u></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>These consolidated financial statements include the assets and 
liabilities of the Endurance Exploration Group, Inc. (formerly Tecton 
Corporation) and its subsidiaries as of June 30, 2016.&#160; The acquisition of 
the membership interests of Endurance LLC and its wholly owned Panamanian 
subsidiary formed to hold the registry of a research vessel occurred as of the 
close of its business on December 31, 2013.</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>The unaudited interim consolidated financial 
statements have been prepared pursuant to the rules and regulations of the U.S. 
Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;).&#160; Certain 
information and footnote disclosures normally included in annual financial 
statements prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted 
in the United States have been condensed or omitted pursuant to such SEC rules 
and regulations, although the Company believes that the disclosures made are 
adequate to make the information not misleading. It is suggested that these 
consolidated financial statements be read in conjunction with the consolidated 
financial statements and the notes thereto, included in the Company&#146;s 
latest Annual Report on Form 10-K.</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>In the opinion of management, all adjustments
consisting of normal recurring adjustments necessary for a fair statement of the
financial position at June 30, 2016 and the results of operations for the three 
and six months ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 and cash flows for the six months 
ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 have been made.&#160; All material intercompany 
transactions have been eliminated.</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'><u>Use of Estimates</u></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>The preparation of financial statements in conformity with U.S. 
generally accepted accounting principles requires management to make estimates
and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and 
disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial 
statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting
period. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><u>Subsequent Events</u></p> 
<p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-autospace:none'>The Company has evaluated subsequent events 
through the filing of this Form 10-Q, to assess the need for potential 
recognition or disclosure in this report. Based upon this evaluation, management
determined that all subsequent events that require recognition in the financial 
statements have been included.</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left;text-
autospace:none'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><u>Cash and Cash 
Equivalents</u></p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>For purposes of the 
Statements of Cash Flows, the Company considers all highly liquid debt 
instruments purchased with a maturity date of three months or less to be cash 
equivalents. </p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'><u>Offering Costs</u></p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>As 
of June 30, 2016, the Company has incurred $30,875 of deferred offering costs 
associated with the planned sale of securities.&#160; This amount is included on
the balance sheet in prepaid expenses and deferred costs.&#160; These costs will
be netted against proceeds upon completion of the offering, or they will be 
expensed if the offering is unsuccessful.</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&#160;&#160;&#160; </p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><u>Fixed Assets</u><b> 
</b></p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>Fixed assets are stated at historical cost. 
Depreciation is provided using the straight-line method at rates based on the 
assets&#146; estimated useful lives which are normally between three and ten 
years. &#160;When retired or otherwise disposed, the related carrying value and 
accumulated depreciation are removed from the respective accounts and the net 
difference less any amount realized from disposition, is reflected in earnings. 
Leasehold improvements are amortized over their estimated useful lives or lease 
term, if shorter. Equipment and major overhaul items (such as engines or 
generators) that enhance or extend the useful life of vessel related assets 
qualify to be capitalized and depreciated over the useful life or remaining life
of that asset, whichever is shorter. Certain major repair items required by 
industry standards to ensure a vessel&#146;s seaworthiness also qualify to be 
capitalized and depreciated over the period of time until the next scheduled 
planned major maintenance for that item. All other repairs and maintenance are 
accounted for under the direct-expensing method and are expensed when incurred. 
</p> <p align="left"
 style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><u>Impairment of Long-Lived 
Assets</u></p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>The Company reviews long-lived assets for impairment whenever 
events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of such 
assets may not be recoverable.&#160; Fair value is determined based on 
discounted cash flows or appraised values, depending on the nature of the 
assets. As of June 30, 2016 and 2015, there were no impairment losses recognized
for long-lived assets.</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'><u>Income Taxes</u></p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>The
Company uses the liability method to record income tax activity. Deferred taxes 
are determined based upon the estimated future tax effects of differences 
between the financial reporting and tax reporting bases of assets and 
liabilities given the provisions of currently enacted tax laws.</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>The accounting for uncertainty in income 
taxes recognized in an enterprise&#146;s financial statements uses the threshold
of more-likely-than-not to be sustained upon examination for inclusion or 
exclusion. Measurement of the tax uncertainty occurs if the recognition 
threshold has been met. </p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'><u>Net Earnings (Losses) Per Common Share</u></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>The Company computes earnings (loss) per share by dividing net 
earnings (loss) by the weighted average number of shares of common stock and 
dilutive common stock equivalents outstanding during the year. Dilutive common 
stock equivalents may&nbsp;consist of shares issuable upon conversion of 
convertible preferred shares and the exercise of the Company's stock options 
(calculated using the treasury stock method).&#160; As of June 30, 2016, there 
were 5,574,000 common stock equivalents that were anti-dilutive and were not 
included in the calculation. Common stock issuable is considered outstanding as 
of the original approval date for purposes of earnings per share 
computations.</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'><u>Fair Value of Financial Instruments</u></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>The fair value of financial instruments, which include cash, 
loans receivable, accounts payable and accrued expenses and advances from 
related parties were estimated to approximate their carrying values due to the 
immediate or short-term maturity of these financial instruments. Management is 
of the opinion that the Company is not exposed to significant interest, currency
or credit risks arising from financial instruments.</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white'><u>Comprehensive Income</u></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>The Company records 
comprehensive income as the change in equity of a business during a period from 
transactions and other events and circumstances from non-owner sources. It 
includes all changes in equity during a period except those resulting from 
investments by owners and distributions to owners. Other comprehensive income 
(loss) includes foreign currency translation adjustments and unrealized gains 
and losses on available-for-sale securities. As of June 30, 2016 the Company had
no items that represent comprehensive loss and, therefore, has not included a 
schedule of comprehensive loss in the financial statements.</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white'><u>Stock Based Compensation</u></p> <p align="left"
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>Stock based compensation 
costs are measured at fair value on date of grant and recognition of 
compensation over the service period for awards expected to vest. The Company 
determines the fair value of awards using the Black-Scholes valuation model. 
</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'><u>New Accounting Pronouncements</u></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>The Company reviews new accounting standards as issued. No new 
standards had any material effect on these financial statements. The accounting 
pronouncements issued subsequent to the date of these financial statements that 
were considered significant by management were evaluated for the potential 
effect on these consolidated financial statements. Management does not believe 
any of the subsequent pronouncements will have a material effect on these 
consolidated financial statements as presented and does not anticipate the need 
for any future restatement of these consolidated financial statements because of
the retro-active application of any accounting pronouncements issued subsequent 
to June 30, 2016 through the date these financial statements were issued.</p> 
<span></span>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<th class="th" colspan="1">6 Months Ended</th>

<tr class="re">
<td class="pl " style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a"

</td>
</tr>
<tr class="ro">
<td class="pl " style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_SubstantialDoubtAboutGoingConcernTextBlock', window );">Note B - Going 
Concern Matters</a></td>
<td class="text"><!--egx--><p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><b>NOTE B &#150; GOING 
CONCERN MATTERS</b></p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>The accompanying 
financial statements have been prepared on a going concern basis, which 
contemplates the realization of assets and the satisfaction of liabilities in 
the normal course of business. As shown in the accompanying financial statements
for the period January 19, 2006 (date of inception) to June 30, 2016, the 
Company incurred losses of $6,745,493. The Company has minimal liquid assets. 
These factors, among others, indicate that the Company will be unable to 
continue as a going concern for a reasonable period of time.</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>The Company's 
existence is dependent upon management's ability to develop profitable 
operations and resolve its liquidity problems. The accompanying financial 
statements do not include any adjustments that might result should the Company 
be unable to continue as a going concern.</p><span></span>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<div style="display: none;">
<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData" 
style="display: none;" id="defref_us-gaap_DisclosureTextBlockAbstract">
<tr><td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td></tr>

<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">-

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData"

gaap_SubstantialDoubtAboutGoingConcernTextBlock">
<tr><td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td></tr>
<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>The entire disclosure when substantial doubt is raised 
about the ability to continue as a going concern. Includes, but is not limited 
to, principal conditions or events that raised substantial doubt about the 
ability to continue as a going concern, management's evaluation of the 
significance of those conditions or events in relation to the ability to meet 
its obligations, and management's plans that alleviated or are intended to 
mitigate the conditions or events that raise substantial doubt about the ability
to continue as a going concern.</p></div>
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+

<td class="text"><!--egx--><p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><b>NOTE C &#150; ACQUISITION 
OF ENDURANCE EXPLORATION GROUP LLC MEMBERSHIP INTERESTS</b></p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>On December 31, 2013, the 
Company acquired 100% of the membership interests of Endurance Exploration 
Group, LLC, a Florida limited liability company (&#147;Endurance LLC&#148;) by 
issuing 20,550,539 shares of its common stock.</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>The majority shareholders of the Company also held a majority 
interest in Endurance LLC, and maintained controlling interests in both entities
both before and after the transaction.&#160; Accordingly, the acquisition has 
been accounted for as a corporate reorganization because of the common 
control.&#160; The book value of Endurance LLC at the time of the acquisition 
was as follows:</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <table border="0"

<td class="text"><!--egx--><p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><b>NOTE D &#150; PREPAID 
EXPENSES AND DEFERRED COSTS</b></p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>On May 15, 2015, the
Company entered into an agreement with Eclipse Group, Inc. to provide services, 
equipment and/or personnel in support of anticipated Endurance salvage projects,
to inspect and recover one or more shipwreck cargoes located by Endurance.&#160;
The Company issued 2,000,000 common shares at $.25 per share with a value of 
$500,000.&#160; These shares represent a prepayment for Eclipse services 
pursuant to a schedule of agreed upon costs and rates.&#160; Eclipse will 
invoice the Company on a monthly basis as services are rendered.&#160; During 
the year ended December 31, 2015, Eclipse rendered $150,000 of the services 
outlined in this agreement.&#160; As of June 30, 2016, the Company has not 
received any additional invoices for services outlined in this agreement, and 
consequently the remaining balance of $350,000 is included in prepaid expenses 
along with $30,875 of deferred issuance costs for a total of $380,875 at June 
30, 2016.</p><span></span>

<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>The entire disclosure for long-lived, physical assets used
in the normal conduct of business and not intended for resale. Includes, but is
not limited to, accounting policies and methodology, roll forwards, 
depreciation, depletion and amortization expense, including composite 
depreciation, accumulated depreciation, depletion and amortization expense, 
useful lives and method used, income statement disclosures, assets held for sale
and public utility disclosures.</p></div>

bottom:6.0pt;text-align:right'>155,500</p>
 </td> </tr> </table> </div> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>On 
December 31, 2013, the Company completed the purchase of 100% of the membership 
interests of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC (&#147;Endurance LLC&#148;), from 
its members, Micah Eldred and Carl Dilley, in exchange for 20,550,539 shares of 
the Company&#146;s common stock, valued at $0.0186 per share, based upon the net
book value of the assets of Endurance LLC, $381,173 as of December 31, 2013.</p>
<p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>On December 31, 2013, as a 
consequence of acquiring the membership interests of Endurance LLC, the Company 
assumed a liability of Endurance LLC to Micah Eldred under a demand promissory 
note, dated June 19, 2012, in the original principal amount of $60,000, bearing 
interest at 5%.&#160; The note has no stipulated maturity date, and the balance 
due under the note at June 30, 2016, including accrued interest, was 
$72,909.</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>The Company has entered into
a contract with Island Capital Management, LLC, which is related through common 
shareholders, to serve as its transfer agent.&#160; It did not charge the 
Company for its services during the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 or
2015, as management has deemed it to be immaterial.</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>The Company has entered into
a contract with Proxy &amp; Printing, LLC, which is related through common 
shareholders, to provide the Company with printing and other services relating 
to its filings with the SEC.&#160; It did not charge the Company for its 
services during the three and six months ended June 30, 2016 or 2015, as 
management has deemed it to be immaterial.</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>On 
June 23, 2014, the Company entered into a contract with Eclipse Group Inc. 
(&#147;Eclipse&#148;) for Eclipse to provide personnel and services to the 
Company in connection with the operation and monitoring of a remotely operated 
vehicle (&#147;ROV&#148;) in connection with our investigation of a suspected 
shipwreck located off the coast of New England. Steven Saint Amour, who serves 
as a member of the Company&#146;s Board of Directors, and Joan Saint Amour are 
the principal shareholders and officers of Eclipse.&#160; The contract provides 
that Eclipse will provide 2 people, including Mr. Saint Amour, for approximately
four 12-hour days to operate and monitor the ROV, which will be provided by the 
Company.&#160; The Company will issue 100,000 shares of common stock to Mr. 
Saint Amour, with an agreed value of $25,000, under the contract, and reimburse 
Eclipse in cash for its cost for the second ROV technician.&#160; The Company 
will also pay Eclipse in cash its cost plus 15% for all third party costs 
incurred by Eclipse, and provide Mr. Saint Amour and the second technician with 
food and lodging during the assignment.</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>On September 3, 
2014, the Company entered into a contract with Overseas Marine Vessel Corp, LLC 
(&#147;OMVC&#148;) pursuant to which it will provide the Marine Vessel Manisee 
in support of an estimated 10-day mission to investigate, identify and recovery 
artifacts from one or more shipwrecks located in our search area off the coast 
of New England.&#160; We will reimburse OMVC in cash for all its out-of-pocket 
expenses only, including but not limited to, mooring, food, fuel, lube, 
satellite communications and crew costs.&#160; Toni Eldred, the spouse of Micah 
Eldred, is a fifty percent owner of OMVC, and Micah Eldred is the co-manager of 
OMVC. </p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-autospace:none'>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered 
into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC 
(&#147;Endeavour&#148;) relating to the conversion of indebtedness to Endeavour 
in the amount of $85,000. This amount represents the related party debt payable 
to Endeavour as of that date.&#160; The terms of the agreement allowed for 
Endeavour to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 per share.&#160; 
Endeavour converted all of such debt into shares, as a result of which we issued
340,000 shares to Endeavour.&#160; </p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-autospace:none'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none'>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered into a Debt Conversion
Agreement with Micah Eldred relating to the conversion of indebtedness to Micah 
Eldred in the amount of $143,333. This amount represents the related party debt 
payable to Micah Eldred as of that date.&#160; The terms of the agreement 
allowed for Micah Eldred to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 per 
share.&#160; Micah Eldred converted all of such debt into shares, as a result of
which we issued 573,333 shares to Micah Eldred. </p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered into a Debt Conversion 
Agreement with Carl &amp; Heather Dilley relating to the conversion of 
indebtedness to Carl &amp; Heather Dilley in the amount of $45,867 and $25,800 
respectively. This amount represents the related party debt payable to Carl 
&amp; Heather Dilley as of that date.&#160; The terms of the agreement allowed 
for Carl &amp; Heather Dilley to convert this debt into common stock at $0.25 
per share.&#160; Carl &amp; Heather Dilley converted all of such debt into
shares, as a result of which we issued 183,467 and 103,200 shares to Carl &amp; 
Heather Dilley respectively.</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>During the six months ended June 30, 2016, 
Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC made net advances to the Company in the 
aggregate amount of $140,000, in order to provide the Company with funds to 
carry on its operations. &#160;These advances do not bear interest, are 
unsecured and have no specific terms of repayment.&#160; As of June 30, 2016, 
the aggregate amount of such advances outstanding was $235,500. Interest has not
been imputed on this balance as management has deemed it to be 
immaterial.</p><span></span>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<tr><td><div class="body" style="padding: 2px;">
<a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div><p>The entire disclosure for related party transactions. 
Examples of related party transactions include transactions between (a) a parent
company and its subsidiary; (b) subsidiaries of a common parent; (c) and entity 
and its principal owners; and (d) affiliates.</p></div>

<td class="text"><!--egx--><p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-

TRANSACTIONS AND REVERSE SPLIT</b></p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;background:white'>&nbsp;</p> <p 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
autospace:none'>On February 12, 2015, the Company entered into a Debt Conversion
Agreement with Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC (&#147;Endeavour&#148;) 
relating to the conversion of indebtedness to Endeavour in the amount of 
$85,000. This amount represents the related party debt payable to Endeavour as 
of that date.&#160; The terms of the agreement allowed for Endeavour to convert 
this debt into common stock at $0.25 per share.&#160; Endeavour converted all of
such debt into shares, as a result of which we issued 340,000 shares to 
Endeavour.&#160; </p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-autospace:none'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-

Company entered into a Debt Conversion Agreement with Micah Eldred relating to 
the conversion of indebtedness to Micah Eldred in the amount of $143,333. This 
amount represents the related party debt payable to Micah Eldred as of that 
date.&#160; The terms of the agreement allowed for Micah Eldred to convert this 
debt into common stock at $0.25 per share.&#160; Micah Eldred converted all of 
such debt into shares, as a result of which we issued 573,333 shares to Micah

investors in fulfillment of stock subscriptions received.</p> <p align="left"

align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>On May 15, 2015, the Company issued 2,000,000 common shares to 
Eclipse Group, Inc. at $.25 per share as prepayment for certain salvage services
pursuant to an agreement entered into on the same date.&#160; Steven Saint 
Amour, who serves as a member of our Board of Directors, and Joan Saint Amour 
are the principal shareholders and officers of Eclipse.</p> <p align="left"

<th class="tl" colspan="1" rowspan="2"><div style="width: 200px;"><strong>Note H
- Warrants and Options<br></strong></div></th>
<th class="th" colspan="1">6 Months Ended</th>
</tr>
<tr><th class="th"><div>Jun. 30, 2016</div></th></tr>
<tr class="re">
<td class="pl " style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-

<tr class="ro">
<td class="pl custom" style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 
'defref_fil_WarrantsAndOptionsDisclosureTextBlock', window );">Note H - Warrants
and Options</a></td>
<td class="text"><!--egx--><p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><b>NOTE H &#150; WARRANTS AND
OPTIONS</b></p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify;text-align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>As 
of June 30, 2016, the Company had outstanding non-qualified options to purchase 
5,574,000 shares of our common stock at any time prior to their expiration 
dates, with an exercise price of $0.25 per share.</p> <p align="left" 
style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-
align:left'>&nbsp;</p> <p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'>The following table 
represents stock option activity as of and for the six months ended June 30,

- Income Taxes<br></strong></div></th>
<th class="th" colspan="1">6 Months Ended</th>
</tr>
<tr><th class="th"><div>Jun. 30, 2016</div></th></tr>
<tr class="re">
<td class="pl " style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-

<td class="text">&#160;<span></span>
</td>

<tr class="ro">
<td class="pl " style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_IncomeTaxDisclosureTextBlock', window );">Note I - Income Taxes</a></td>
<td class="text"><!--egx--><p align="left" style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-align:left'><b>NOTE I &#150; INCOME 
TAXES</b></p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-
align:justify'>There is no current or deferred income tax expense or benefit 
allocated to continuing operations for the period ended June 30, 2016 and 2015. 
The Company has not recognized an income tax benefit for its operating losses 
generated through June 30, 2016 based on uncertainties concerning the
Company&#146;s ability to generate taxable income in future 
periods.&nbsp;&nbsp;The tax benefit is offset by a valuation allowance 
established against deferred tax assets arising from operating losses and other 
temporary differences, the realization of which could not be considered more 
likely than not.&nbsp;&nbsp;In future periods, tax benefits and related deferred
tax assets will be recognized when management considers realization of such 
amounts to be more likely than not.</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p> <p style='margin:0in;margin-
bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'>For income tax purposes the Company has 
available a net operating loss carry-forward of approximately $6,745,000 from 
inception to June 30, 2016, which will expire, unless used to offset future 
federal taxable income beginning in 2024.&#160; The tax years ending December 
31, 2013 through December 31, 2014 are open for inspection by both Federal and 
State Agencies.</p><span></span>
</td>
